SIMPLE: treat
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treat
<hw>Treat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Treated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Treating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<er>OE</er>. <ets>treten</ets>,
OF. <ets>traitier</ets>, F. <ets>traiter</ets>, from L.
<ets>tractare</ets> to draw violently, to handle, manage, treat, v.
intens. from <ets>trahere</ets>, <ets>tractum</ets>, to draw. See
<er>Trace</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf. <er>Entreat</er>,
<er>Retreat</er>, <er>Trait</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To handle; to
manage; to use; to bear one's self toward; <as>as, to <ex>treat</ex>
prisoners cruelly; to <ex>treat</ex> children kindly.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To discourse on; to handle in a particular manner,
in writing or speaking; <as>as, to <ex>treat</ex> a subject
diffusely</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To entertain with food or drink, especially the
latter, as a compliment, or as an expression of friendship or regard;
<as>as, to <ex>treat</ex> the whole company</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To negotiate; to settle; to make terms for.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>treat</qex> the peace, a hundred senators⟦br⟧
Shall be commissioned.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To care for medicinally or
surgically; to manage in the use of remedies or appliances; <as>as, to
<ex>treat</ex> a disease, a wound, or a patient</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To subject to some action; to apply something to;
<as>as, to <ex>treat</ex> a substance with sulphuric acid</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To entreat; to beseech.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ld. Berners.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Treat
<hw>Treat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
discourse; to handle a subject in writing or speaking; to make
discussion; -- usually with <xex>of</xex>; <as>as, Cicero
<ex>treats</ex> of old age and of duties</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And, shortly of this story for to <qex>treat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now of love they <qex>treat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To negotiate; to come to terms of accommodation; --
often followed by <xex>with</xex>; <as>as, envoys were appointed to
<ex>treat</ex> with France</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inform us, will the emperor <qex>treat</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give a gratuitous entertainment, esp. of food or
drink, as a compliment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Treat
<hw>Treat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A parley; a
conference.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid him battle without further <qex>treat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An entertainment given as an expression of
regard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which affords entertainment; a gratification; a
satisfaction; <as>as, the concert was a rich
<ex>treat</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treatable</ent>⟦br⟧
